### Which @angular/* package(s) are relevant/related to the feature request?

core

### Description

Hi!

There is no proper way to access any lifecycle hook other than `ngOnDestroy` outside a declarable's implementation and without inheritance.

Providing a way of accessing lifecycle hooks outside the component, through DI, for instance, could allow a couple of libraries and upcoming libraries to provide reusable logic linked to lifecycle hooks. _(e.g. custom change detection strategies, hooking into local stores like `RxState` or `ComponentStore`)_

Providing these lifecycle hooks as an observable could also allow some interesting reactive patterns.

### Proposed solution

This could be provided through a `LifecycleHooks` service like this:

```ts
class LifecycleHooks {
  init$: Observable<void>;
  changes$: Observable<SimpleChanges>;
  destroy$: Observable<void>;
  ...
}
```

Here is a working example. In this example, the `LinkLifecycleHooks()` does the magic that wouldn't be required if this was implemented natively.

https://stackblitz.com/edit/angular-lifecycle-hooks-service?file=apps%2Flifecycle%2Fsrc%2Fapp%2Fapp.component.ts

Here are some other use case examples:

1. custom change detection strategy
```ts
@Component()
class MyCmp {
  constructor(injector: Injector) {
    useLowPriorityStrategy(injector);
  }
}

function useLowPriorityStrategy(injector) {

  const cdr = injector.get(ChangeDetectorRef);
  const { init$, changes$, destroy$ } = injector.get(LifecycleHooks);

  cdr.detach();

  merge(init$, changes$)
    .pipe(
      debounceTime(50),
      takeUntil(destroy$)
    )
    .subscribe(() => cdr.markForCheck());

}
```

2. rx-based reactivity
```ts
@Component()
class MyCmp {
  @Input() itemId?: string;

  itemId$ = this._hooks.changes$
    .pipe(
      map(changes => changes['itemId'],
      filter(change => change != null),
      map(change => change.currentValue)
   );

 destroy$ = this._hooks.destroy$;

 item$ = combineLatest(
   this.itemId$,
   this._hooks.afterViewInit$ // wait for view init just as an example
 ).pipe(
   switchMap(([itemId]) => ...))
 )

 constructor(private _hooks: LifecycleHooks) {}

}
```


### Alternatives considered

Use a custom decorator.

